						<p>Hi-</p>
<p>So Facebook is down right now, and their plugin has a &#8220;call home&#8221; function that depends on a transient to only run once per day.</p>
<p>Since FB is down, it was running that call home on every load, and timing out.  Using:</p>
<p><code>./wp-cli.phar transient set wc_facebook_connection_refresh XXX YYY</code></p>
<p>I set the transient but it didn&#8217;t &#8220;stick&#8221;, and the site was still failing to load.</p>
<p>I tossed together a quick program to do it:</p>
<pre><code>&lt;?php
require_once( dirname( __FILE__ ) . &#039;/wp-load.php&#039; );

$r = get_transient(&#039;wc_facebook_connection_refresh&#039;);
echo &quot;Initial Load: &quot;.print_r($r, true).PHP_EOL;
set_transient( &#039;wc_facebook_connection_refresh&#039;, time(), 2*DAY_IN_SECONDS );
$r = get_transient(&#039;wc_facebook_connection_refresh&#039;);
echo &quot;After Set: &quot;.print_r($r, true).PHP_EOL;
</code></pre>
<p>Which still was not setting it consistently.</p>
<p>After looking into the code, I found this:</p>
<pre><code>function _can_cache() {
		/**
		 * Don&#039;t cache in console mode
		 */
		if ( PHP_SAPI === &#039;cli&#039; ) {
			$this-&gt;cache_reject_reason = &#039;Console mode&#039;;

			return false;
		}</code></pre>
<p>In ObjectCache_WpObject_Regular.php</p>
